An in between is to have the unit tests in the same package, but in
different directories.  This at leasts allows for you to test public and
package as well as have them separated..just a thought.



-----Original Message-----
From: Stevens, Timothy J. (LNG-MBC)
[mailto:timothy.j.stevens@...] 
Sent: Friday, March 29, 2002 12:47 PM
To: &#39;junit@yahoogroups.com&#39;
Subject: RE: [junit] testing private methods


      Many of my tests wind up being nearly as long as the class being
tested... I have no desire to double the size of my code with tests.
Plus,
tests that exist within the classes they are testing will ultimately get
compiled along with the classes, increasing the size of your
distributions
needlessly.

      I go with the separate-yet-parallel directory structure route, and
tend to make most methods protected rather than private to allow them to
be
tested. I&#39;m sure someone will chime in shortly for logic surrounding
only
testing public methods.

      -tim

-----Original Message-----
From: David Stagner [mailto:dstagner@...]
Sent: Friday, March 29, 2002 2:38 PM
To: junit@yahoogroups.com
Subject: Re: [junit] testing private methods


Nilesh Thali wrote:

&gt; Actually, we would like to keep our tests as a completely separate
package
to
&gt; 
&gt; prevent it from obscuring the actual code base...

Choose your poison, then. If you want to keep your test classes 
completely separate from the classes tested, then you&#39;ll only be testing

the public interface (and you need to feel certain all your private 
methods work when they can only be tested indirectly via the public 
interface). If you want to test private methods directly, you must run 
your tests as inner classes.

Why do you think tests &quot;obscure&quot; the code base, though? If you use an 
inner class, just put it at the very bottom of the source file, and 
programmers should be able to just ignore it. If you use a consistent 
naming scheme, programmers can also ignore test methods in whatever IDE 
you&#39;re using. Alternately, you could put the tests in separate classes 
in the same package, so you can test package-local methods.

Personally, i don&#39;t like the idea of putting unit tests in a separate 
package, for two reasons - first, the tests would only have access to 
public methods, not package or private methods. This makes test-first 
coding harder, as the private methods can only be observed indirectly. 
And second, it makes it too easy to ignore the test suite, &quot;just this 
one time&quot;, which leads to untested code. But this is very much my own 
opinion on how things should be done.
